# JavaScript / TypeScript (FormForge)

Applies to `src/` today and `frontend/` after the monorepo split.

## Types

- Prefer `strict` TypeScript. No `any` unless documented and unavoidable.
- Use `unknown` + narrowing for external/API data.
- Domain types live in `src/types/` (`form.ts`, `response.ts`).

## Structure

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — mixed concerns
async function submitResponse(formId: string, answers: Answers) {
  const validated = validateAnswers(answers);
  const res = await fetch(`/api/forms/${formId}/responses`, { method: "POST", body: JSON.stringify(validated) });
  return res.json();
}

// ✅ GOOD — split validation, transport, orchestration
function validateAnswers(answers: Answers): ValidatedAnswers { ... }
async function createResponse(formId: string, payload: CreateResponsePayload): Promise<Response> { ... }
async function submitResponse(formId: string, answers: Answers): Promise<Response> {
  return createResponse(formId, { answers: validateAnswers(answers) });
}
```

## Async & errors

- Always `await` or handle promises — no floating promises.
- Use typed errors at boundaries; avoid bare `throw "string"`.
- Reuse `src/lib/api.ts` patterns for consistent API errors.

## Modules

- Named exports for shared modules.
- Keep side effects out of module top-level except app entry/bootstrap.

## React / Next.js

- App Router: routes in `src/app/`, UI in `src/components/`, API client in `src/lib/`.
- Server Components for data fetching; Client Components only for interactivity (`"use client"`).
- **Interim:** call same-origin `/api/*` Route Handlers.
- **Post-migration:** call FastAPI via `src/lib/` helpers (`API_URL` server-side) — no business logic in components.
- Builder state: Zustand (`src/stores/use-builder-store.ts`). Extract hooks when logic is reused or a component exceeds ~80 lines.
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` for browser-safe config only. Secrets stay server-side (`AUTH_SECRET`, `API_URL`).

## Style

- Prefer `const`; use `let` only when reassigned.
- Early returns over nested `if/else`.
- Destructure at the top of functions when it improves readability.
